   <h1>Re: [VB] disc brake front</h1>
   <b>Claralw_at_aol_dot_com</b><br/>
   <i>2000-07-07 17:52:18+00</i><br/>
   <br/>
   <pre>I had a 59 SC with a bay front beam in it. Ball joints, drum brakes. There 
were several things POs had done to this SC, but the bay beam is the case in 
point.  Yes the nose was slightly turned up.   I was thinking of putting 15" 
rims on the back, It had 14"  all the way around, I though put 15" on the 
back leave 14" on the front could compensate but I never bothered it wasn't 
all that important to me.



In a message dated 7/6/00 3:29:49 AM Pacific Daylight Time, 
cal4570_at_concentric_dot_net writes:

<< 
 The bay swap will raise the front, whether you do it the bolt in way or the
 hard way. Bay beams have higher ride heights. The rear in the Westfailure
 has a Ford 9 inch on leaf springs, and the front required coilovers to raise
 it to stock height. This will not be the case in a non V8 mid-engine
 conversion. The bay beam is pushed all the way up when it bolts in, there is
 no 2 inches to move it. You must cut and turn the beam if you want it lower.
 There are no shortcuts when hacking up a splittie. 8^)
 
 Kyle
 57 single cab
 59 single cab
 61 Kombi
 67 Westfailure
 57 Oval
 
 > and so would the front be higher than you would like it ?
 > and did you also have to lift the saggy rear ( V8) ?
 > is the whole ride now too high ?
 > perhaps the rear was re-splined to accomodate the V8
 > but the front still rides higher...
 > it would seem better to stuff in the whole front beam,
 > ignoring the obvious 2-bolt hole savings, in favor of a
 > more correct ride height. by pushing the beam up those
 > two inches and making 4  new mounting holes
  >></pre>


